Status: disputed; disputed; MOSCOW. March 5 (Interfax) - Russian forces have declared the opening of humanitarian passages at 10 a.m. Moscow time on Saturday and a ceasefire that would enable civilians to leave Mariupol and Volnovakha. "Humanitarian passages and exit routes have been coordinated with the Ukrainian side," the ministry said. ;;;; KYIV. March 5 (Interfax-Ukraine) - Pavlo Kyrylenko, head of the Donetsk regional military-civilian administration (subordinated to Kyiv), has said he can confirm that a ceasefire has been agreed to facilitate the evacuation of residents of Volnovakha and Mariupol starting 9:00 a.m. Kyiv Time (10:00 a.m. Moscow Time). ;;;;; KYIV. March 5 (Interfax-Ukraine) - Pavlo Kyrylenko, head of the Donetsk regional military-civilian administration (subordinated to Kyiv), has announced the establishment of a ceasefire from 9:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m. Kyiv Time (10:00 a.m. to 17:00 a.m. Moscow Time), with the evacuation of civilians from Mariupol starting at 11:00 a.m. Kyiv Time."Officially. A humanitarian corridor has been established along the following route: Mariupol - Mykilske - Rozivka - Polohy - Orikhiv - Zaporizhzhya," Kyrylenko wrote on his Telegram channel on Saturday morning. KYIV. March 5 (Interfax-Ukraine) - Ukrainian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Reintegration of Temporarily Occupied Territories Iryna Vereshchuk has announced the establishment of a humanitarian corridor from Volnovakha and Mariupol to evacuate local civilians.
 "Via the International Committee of the Red Cross's (ICRC) mediation, we agreed upon the routes, the movement of a column, and a plan for the delivery of humanitarian cargo, and we have obtained confirmation from the Russian side," Vereshchuk said at a press briefing on Saturday.
 Ukraine plans to evacuate over 200,000 people along the Mariupol - Mykilske - Rozivka - Bilmak - Polohe - Orikhiv - Zaporizhzhya route and over 15,000 people along the Volnovakha - Valeryanivka - Novoandriyivka - Kyrylivka - Vuhledar - Pokrovsk - Zaporizhzhya route, Vereshchuk said.
 The ICRC is acting as a guarantor of the ceasefire during the evacuation, Vereshchuk said.  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/75561/?sphrase_id=79069 ;;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/75577/?sphrase_id=79069 ;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/75579/?sphrase_id=79069 ;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/75602/?sphrase_id=79069 ;;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/75616/?sphrase_id=79069

Status: proposed route/outcome unknown; Russia submitted an initiative to the Ukrainian authorities to open ten humanitarian corridors on March 9 to evacuate civilians and foreign citizens from Kyiv, Chernihiv, Sumy, Kharkiv, and Mariupol, including a humanitarian corridor from each of these cities leading to Russia and one corridor from each of these cities transiting Kyiv-controlled territories to Poland, Moldova and Romania, he said.
 "Only three routes were agreed: one from Kyiv to the south, one from Sumy to Poltava and one from Mariupol to Zaporizhzhya. But another three were proposed: from Enerhodar to Zaporizhzhya, from Volnovakha to Pokrovsk, and from Izyum to Lozova," Mizintsev said.  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/76105/?sphrase_id=79069

Status: proposed route/outcome unknown; KYIV. March 14 (Interfax-Ukraine) - Ten humanitarian corridors in Ukraine have been agreed upon as of March 14, Ukrainian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Reintegration of Temporarily Occupied Territories Iryna Vereshchuk said in a video address on Monday. These include humanitarian routes in the Kyiv region (from Bohdanivka, Novobohdanivka, Peremoha, and Bobryk to Brovary, from Hostomel, Nemyshayevo, Vorzel, and Dmytrivka to Bilohorodka) and in the Luhansk region (from Severodonetsk, Popasna, and Hirske to Slovyansk), she said.  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/76647/?sphrase_id=78695

Status: successful; Yes; "Over 160 private cars have managed to depart from Mariupol via the route to the city of Berdiansk by 1 p.m. Mariupol residents were driving along the route of the humanitarian corridor agreed in advance from Mariupol via the exit towards the village of Melekine, [past] the village of Portovske, the village of Manhush, Berdiansk, Tokmak [to] Zaporizhzhya," the city council said on its Telegram channel.  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/76686/?sphrase_id=78695

Status: unsuccessful; unsuccessful, only out of town evacuation, no humanitarian aid from Berdyansk; "Nine humanitarian corridors have been agreed for today. The Donetsk region: a humanitarian convoy carrying dozens of tonnes of water, medications and food will depart from the city of Berdyansk ;;; MOSCOW. March 16 (Interfax) - More than 31,000 civilians were evacuated from Ukraine's Mariupol in the past 24 hours, the Russian Defense Ministry said. [Zaporizhzhya region] to the city of Mariupol [Donetsk region]. On its way back, it will collect and transport women, children and all those in need of it from Mariupol to Zaporizhzhya," Vereshchuk said in a video address published on the Telegram channel of the Office of the Ukrainian President.::: "We have no corridors in the Luhansk region today, yet they worked for two days and they worked well. The problem with Mariupol;;; "A humanitarian operation is underway in Mariupol. As many as 31,367 civilians were safely evacuated from the unblocked city via humanitarian corridors in the past 24 hours," head of the Russian National Defense Control Center Mikhail Mizintsev said. persists. Our humanitarian convoy has been unable to reach Mariupol from Berdyansk," Vereshchuk said at a press briefing on Tuesday.
 
 The humanitarian trucks have been unable to cover the 84-kilometer distance between Berdyansk and Mariupol for days, she said.
 
 Meanwhile, the Mariupol City Council said earlier on Tuesday that 2,000 vehicles of evacuees left Mariupol for Zaporizhzhya and another 2,000 vehicles were leaving the city as of 2 p.m. local time (3 p.m. Moscow time) on Tuesday.;;;; Out of the overall number of those evacuated on Tuesday, 20,000 people left Mariupol on their own vehicles, Zelensky said.  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/76739/?sphrase_id=78694 ;;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/76777/?sphrase_id=78694 ;;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/76876/? ;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/76876/?sphrase_id=81982;;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/76822/?sphrase_id=81982

Status: unsuccessful; unsuccessful; KYIV. March 18 (Interfax-Ukraine) - Eight of the nine humanitarian corridors planned for March 17 worked, Ukrainian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Reintegration of Temporarily Occupied Territories Iryna Vereshchuk said.
 
 "Eight of the planned nine humanitarian corridors worked today. [...] The corridor for humanitarian assistance from Kharkiv to Vovchansk did not work. We continue working on coordinating routes for delivering humanitarian assistance," Vereshchuk told a briefing on Thursday evening.  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/76962/?sphrase_id=81982

Status: successful; 156 civilians evacuated via buses; 156 evacuated from Mariupol's Azovstal steel plant. President Volodymyr Zelenskiy has confirmed 156 people who were successfully evacuated from the Azovstal steel plant in Mariupol have arrived in Zaporizhzhia on Tuesday.  see source: https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2022/may/03/russia-ukraine-war-moscow-plans-to-annex-donetsk-and-luhansk-us-says-britain-pledges-another-300m-in-military-aid-live

Status: successful; 344 civilians evacuated;  evacuation from Azovstal "and suburbs" see source: https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2022/may/04/russia-ukraine-war-russia-attacks-azovstal-steel-plant-after-first-evacuated-civilians-reach-safety-live?filterKeyEvents=false&page=with:block-6272ffc88f08a298acd038f6#block-6272ffc88f08a298acd038f6

Status: proposed route/outcome unknown; MOSCOW. March 7 (Interfax) - Russia has declared a ceasefire starting 10:00 a.m. on March 7 and will open humanitarian corridors for the evacuation of civilians from Kyiv, Mariupol, Kharkiv, and Sumy, the Russian interagency humanitarian response staff in Ukraine said on Monday. ;;;;; MOSCOW. March 7 (Interfax) - The Russian military has accused Ukrainian nationalists of disrupting the work of humanitarian corridors. "We monitored closely using objective control means, including drones, no practical events to prepare humanitarian convoys were conducted, no one came to the opened humanitarian corridors," Col. Gen. Mikhail Mizintsev, the head of the Russian National Defense Control Center, said. "It has been established that nationalists are just not letting civilians and foreign citizens out of the said populated areas under threat of physical violence," Mizintsev said.  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/75807/?sphrase_id=79069 ;;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/75822/?sphrase_id=79069 ;;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/75842/?sphrase_id=79069 ;;; https://inews.co.uk/news/what-is-humanitarian-corridor-meaning-why-putin-offering-evacuate-ukraine-russia-belarus-1501680?ico=in-line_link
To: Gomel (Belarus) to be transfered to Russia by air

Status: proposed route/outcome unknown; MOSCOW. March 8 (Interfax) - Russia will declare a temporary ceasefire on Wednesday to provide for the functioning of humanitarian corridors from Kyiv, Chernihiv, Sumy, Kharkiv, and Mariupol, the Russian interagency humanitarian response coordination staff in Ukraine said in a statement. ;;;; KYIV. March 9 (Interfax-Ukraine) - The availability of the Sumy-Poltava humanitarian corridor was extended on Wednesday, head of the Sumy regional state administration Dmytro Zhivitsky said. "The team of negotiators was working through the night, and the availability of a humanitarian passage from Sumy to Poltava was extended today, on March 9, 2022, from 9 a.m. to 9 p.m.," Zhivitsky said on Telegram on Wednesday. "You can use your own vehicles. Besides, at about 2 p.m., we will bring back 22 buses from Poltava to Sumy; the buses formed the first convoy yesterday. They will be available to pregnant women, women with children, senior citizens, and people with disabilities," he said. ;;;; Russia offers Wednesday cease-fire for humanitarian corridors
 The Russian military said it would offer a cease-fire starting at 10 a.m. local time (0700 UTC) Wednesday to allow civilians to escape from four Ukrainian cities, according to Russia's TASS news agency. 
 A senior military official told TASS that information about humanitarian corridors from Kyiv, Chernihiv, Sumy, Kharkiv and Mariupol would be sent to Ukrainian Deputy Prime Minister Iryna Vereshchuk.
 Ukraine has yet to respond to the offer. 
 Similar attempts to enable safe evacuation of civilians have been only partially successful, with allegations of shelling on some routes, disputes over the routes themselves, and other complications.  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/75969/?sphrase_id=79069 ;;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/75987/?sphrase_id=79069 ;;; https://www.dw.com/en/ukraine-civilian-evacuation-efforts-hampered-by-continued-fighting-as-it-happened/a-61046457

"The team of negotiators was working through the night, and the availability of a humanitarian passage from Sumy to Poltava was extended today, on March 9, 2022, from 9 a.m. to 9 p.m.," Zhivitsky said on Telegram on Wednesday. "You can use your own vehicles. Besides, at about 2 p.m., we will bring back 22 buses from Poltava to Sumy; the buses formed the first convoy yesterday. They will be available to pregnant women, women with children, senior citizens, and people with disabilities," he said. ;;;; Russia offers Wednesday cease-fire for humanitarian corridors
 The Russian military said it would offer a cease-fire starting at 10 a.m. local time (0700 UTC) Wednesday to allow civilians to escape from four Ukrainian cities, according to Russia's TASS news agency. 
 A senior military official told TASS that information about humanitarian corridors from Kyiv, Chernihiv, Sumy, Kharkiv and Mariupol would be sent to Ukrainian Deputy Prime Minister Iryna Vereshchuk.
 Ukraine has yet to respond to the offer. 
 Similar attempts to enable safe evacuation of civilians have been only partially successful, with allegations of shelling on some routes, disputes over the routes themselves, and other complications.  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/75969/?sphrase_id=79069

text: Status: successful; evacuation successful claims Enerhodar mayor; KYIV. March 9 (Interfax-Ukraine) - Dmytro Orlov, mayor of Enerhodar in the Zaporizhzhya region, has reported a ceasefire established at 9 a.m. local time (10:00 a.m. Moscow time) on Wednesday and the opening under the aegis of the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) of a humanitarian corridor from Zaporizhzhya to Enerhodar and a green passage to Zaporizhzhya for evacuating civilians. ;;;; ZAPORIZHZHYA. March 9 (Interfax-Ukraine) - Buses with evacuees from Enerhodar (Zaporizhzhya region, Ukraine), which is now controlled by Russian troops, have arrived in Zaporizhzhya. The evacuation was carried out through a "green corridor" between the two cities and this evening the column of evacuation buses "reached the point of destination," Enerhodar mayor Dmytro Orlov said on Telegram. There were also other "citizens in personal vehicles" who exited via the corridor and were now arriving in the suburbs of Zaporizhzhya, he said. According to the Zaporizhzhya city council, child evacuees were placed at kindergartens and given food. After that, they will be examined by medics. Earlier the Russian Defense Ministry said that on February 28, its troops "took control over Enerhodar, Zaporizhzhya nuclear power plant and the adjacent area." On March 9 the ministry said a "humanitarian corridor" was opened from Enerhodar to Zaporizhzhya.  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/76011/?sphrase_id=79069 ;;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/76131/?sphrase_id=79069

Status: successful; evacuation successful claims Enerhodar mayor; KYIV. March 9 (Interfax-Ukraine) - Evacuation buses have departed Enerhodar to carry residents of the city to Zaporizhzhya, Kyrylo Tymoshenko, deputy head of the Ukrainian presidential office, said in a video on his Telegram account. A column of vehicles is also being formed in the Poltava region to evacuate people from Sumy with support from the Ukrainian Red Cross, he said. It was reported earlier that, starting from 9:00 a.m. local time (10:00 a.m. Moscow Time) until 9:00 p.m., a temporary ceasefire would be declared to facilitate the functioning of humanitarian corridors linking Enerhodar with Zaporizhzhya, Sumy with Poltava, Izyum with Lozova, Mariupol with Zaporizhzhya, Volnovakha with Pokrovsk, and Vorzel, Borodyanka, Irpin, and Hostomel with Kyiv.  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/76072/?sphrase_id=79069

March 19 (Interfax-Ukraine) - Seven out of nine humanitarian corridors operated on Friday, 9,145 people were evacuated, Ukrainian Deputy Prime Minister, Minister for Reintegration of Temporarily Occupied Territories Iryna Vereshchuk said.
 
 A total of 4,972 people were evacuated from Mariupol to Zaporizhzhya, 4,173 people from Sumy region, [including] 3,296 from Sumy, 246 from Trostianets, 50 from Lebedyn, 400 from Konotop, 146 from the Krasnopillia village, 41 from Bolsha Pysarivka. 7 out of 9 functioning; 2 non-functioning not identified ;;; KYIV. Status: successful; succesful evacuation of nearly 6000 civilians (usinig own vehicles); KYIV. March 22 (Interfax-Ukraine) - As many as 8,057 civilians were evacuated through humanitarian corridors on March 22, Kyrylo Tymoshenko, deputy head of the Office of Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky, said.
 "A total of 8,057 people were evacuated via these humanitarian corridors. Of them, 3,007 people from Mariupol reached Zaporizhzhya," Tymoshenko said on Telegram on Monday evening.;;; KYIV. March 23 (Interfax-Ukraine) - More than 7,000 people left Mariupol along humanitarian corridors on March 22, Kyrylo Tymoshenko, deputy head of the Office of Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky, said.
 
 "As a matter of fact, more than 7,000 people were evacuated from Mariupol via humanitarian corridors during the day. They are 1,100 Mariupol residents, who were already in Berdyansk, and nearly 6,000 people who headed from Mariupol to Zaporizhzhya on their own vehicles," Tymoshenko said in televised remarks on Tuesday.  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/77180/?sphrase_id=81981 ;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/77242/?sphrase_id=83678

Status: successful; successful evacuation of citizens by private transportation; Meanwhile, Ukrainian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Reintegration of the Temporarily Occupied Territories Iryna Vereschuk said that nine humanitarian corridors have been approved for Wednesday.
 
 "Nine humanitarian corridors have been approved in the Donetsk region from Mariupol to Zaporizhzhya... Berdyansk-Zaporizhzhya. Twenty-four buses are currently at the entry to Berdyansk. At 10:00 a.m. local time (11:00 a.m. Moscow time), they will enter the city to start evacuation," Vereshchuk said at a press briefing on Wednesday.
 
 There are also plans to open humanitarian corridors in the Zaporizhzhya region: from Polohy to Zaporizhzhya and from Hulyaypole to Zaporizhzhya, she said.
 
 In the Kyiv region, there will be humanitarian corridors from Velyka Dymerka to Brovary, from Bohdanivka to Brovary, from Borodyanka to Bila Tserkva, and from Svetilnya to Brovary.
 
 Humanitarian corridors from Rubezhne to Bakhmut and from Nyzhne to Bakhmut will be opened in the Luhansk region.
 
 "These routes will also transit other cities where buses will stop to collect people - in Lysychansk, Sievierodonetsk...," Vereshchuk said.
 
 Vereshchuk said earlier that Mariupol residents who earlier arrived in Berdyansk were expected to be evacuated from Berdyansk on Wednesday.
 
 "On Wednesday morning, buses will start picking up people from the gathering point near the city sports center," she said in a video address on Tuesday evening.
 
 Buses and a vehicle with petrol for Mariupol residents' cars were also expected to arrive from Zaporizhzhya. A total of 1,100 Mariupol residents, 5,926 of them on their own vehicles, left Berdyansk for Zaporizhzhya on Tuesday. Humanitarian aid was also delivered to Berdyansk, Vereshchuk said. ;;;;; 2,912 residents of Mariupol reached Zaporizhzhya on their own vehicles  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/77242/?sphrase_id=83678 ;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/77284/?sphrase_id=85990

Status: successful; successful evacuation of civilians; Meanwhile, Ukrainian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Reintegration of the Temporarily Occupied Territories Iryna Vereschuk said that nine humanitarian corridors have been approved for Wednesday.
 
 "Nine humanitarian corridors have been approved in the Donetsk region from Mariupol to Zaporizhzhya... Berdyansk-Zaporizhzhya. Twenty-four buses are currently at the entry to Berdyansk. At 10:00 a.m. local time (11:00 a.m. Moscow time), they will enter the city to start evacuation," Vereshchuk said at a press briefing on Wednesday.
 
 There are also plans to open humanitarian corridors in the Zaporizhzhya region: from Polohy to Zaporizhzhya and from Hulyaypole to Zaporizhzhya, she said.
 
 In the Kyiv region, there will be humanitarian corridors from Velyka Dymerka to Brovary, from Bohdanivka to Brovary, from Borodyanka to Bila Tserkva, and from Svetilnya to Brovary.
 
 Humanitarian corridors from Rubezhne to Bakhmut and from Nyzhne to Bakhmut will be opened in the Luhansk region.
 
 "These routes will also transit other cities where buses will stop to collect people - in Lysychansk, Sievierodonetsk...," Vereshchuk said.
 
 Vereshchuk said earlier that Mariupol residents who earlier arrived in Berdyansk were expected to be evacuated from Berdyansk on Wednesday.
 
 "On Wednesday morning, buses will start picking up people from the gathering point near the city sports center," she said in a video address on Tuesday evening.

Status: successful; evacuation of civilians by private vehicles and buses; KYIV. April 11 (Interfax-Ukraine) - As many as 2,824 people were evacuated via humanitarian corridors on Sunday, April 10, Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Reintegration of the Temporarily Occupied Territories of Ukraine Iryna Vereshchuk said. "In total, 2,622 people from Mariupol and Berdyansk have evacuated by their own vehicles and buses to Zaporizhzhya. Of them, 213 are Mariupol residents, and 2,409 are residents of the cities of the Zaporizhzhya region (Rody, Vasylivka, Berdyansk, and Melytopil)," Vereshchuk said on the social media. As many as 202 people were evacuated from the towns of Lysychansk, Severodonetsk, Rubizhne, Kreminna, and Popasna in the Luhansk region. ;;; "Nearly 3,000 people were evacuated on Sunday through humanitarian corridors, including 213 from Mariupol, Ukraine’s deputy prime minister, Iryna Vereshchuk, said." (The Guardian)  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/78077/?sphrase_id=95308;;;;https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2022/apr/10/russia-ukraine-war-latest-zelenskiy-pushes-for-oil-embargo-to-curb-russias-sense-of-impunity-uk-pledges-to-send-more-arms-live?page=with:block-62535bd28f0887d7b40d7c5f

April 14 (Interfax-Ukraine) - A total of 1,567 civilians were evacuated in Ukraine on Wednesday, April 13, Kyrylo Tymoshenko, deputy head of the Office of Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky, said in a statement on Telegram.  see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/78205/?sphrase_id=95307

Status: successful; evacuation of civilians by private vehicles; According to Vereshchuk, nine humanitarian corridors will open for the evacuation of civilians from cities in the Zaporizhzhya, Donetsk and Luhansk regions on Friday, April 15. "Nine humanitarian corridors have been approved for April 15, 2022," Vereshchuk said. Evacuation from Mariupol, Berdyansk, Tokmak and Enerhodar to Zaporizhzhya will be conducted by private vehicles, she said. Evacuation from Sievierodonetsk, Lysychansk, Popasna, Horske and Rubizhne to Bakhmut has also been agreed upon, Vereshchuk said. civilians include 289 persons from Mariupol and 2,043 residents of towns in the Zaporizhzhya region (Polohi, Vasylivka, Berdyansk and Melitopol) see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/78205/?sphrase_id=95307 ;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/78253/?sphrase_id=95307

Status: successful; evacuation of civilians via 4 buses; KYIV. April 20 (Interfax-Ukraine) - A humanitarian corridor for civilians' evacuation from Mariupol will be opened on Wednesday, Ukrainian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Reintegration of the Temporarily Occupied Territories Iryna Vereshchuk said. "We managed to tentatively agree on a humanitarian corridor for women, children and the elderly. The gathering point is the intersection of Taganrogska Street and 130th Taganrog Division Street, at 2:00 p.m. today, on April 20. The convoy's route will be Mariupol-Manhush-Berdyansk-Tokmak-Orekhove-Zaporizhzhya," Vereshchuk said on Telegram. The Ukrainian side has proposed more than 340 humanitarian corridors since February 24. Nearly 300 of them were agreed, but only 176 were actually opened, the ministry's press service said. Corridor via the convoy's route Mariupol-Manhush-Berdyansk-Tokmak-Orekhove-Zaporizhzhya see source: https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/78387/?sphrase_id=95379 ;;; https://interfax.com/newsroom/top-stories/78440/?sphrase_id=95379
